Extend --on-error-reduce to allow also the case where there are several
reductions (but only one of them is marked --on-error-reduce). In that
case, maybe signal a conflict when several reductions are marked. Use
that to deal with statements that could be followed with ELSE.

%reduceonerror should be in the .mly file?

If loop_handle_undo is unused, remove it, as it is costly.

Another argument against testing tokens with [acceptable] is that it is not
clear that our semantic actions are replayable (they have side effects).

When we say "if this list is complete..."
we should also say that if it is not complete, then it can
be continued with a comma, etc.
Same thing for attribute_specifier_list, declarator.

When a nonempty list is expected, there can be hesitation: should we say "an
element is expected", or "a nonempty list is expected"?

Revoir tous les messages d'erreur pour voir où $i peut servir.

